events.name: Google I/O Extended Event
events.description:
Google I/O is an annual developer-focused conference held by Google in San Francisco, California. Google I/O features highly technical, in-depth sessions focused on building web, mobile, and enterprise applications with Google and open web technologies such as Android, Chrome, Chrome OS, Google APIs, Google Web Toolkit, App Engine, and more.

Google I/O was started in 2008. The "I" and "O" stand for input/output, and "Innovation in the Open". The format of the event is similar to that of the Google Developer Day.

The I/O Extended event is a local live streaming event with key notes and sessions held here locally in Hampton Roads

https://www.google.com/events/io/io-extended

events.name: Android Application Penetration Testing 101
events.description:
Want to know more about Android security? Ben Simpson will demonstrate an offensive approach to android application pentesting. 

Some of the ways discussed include Dex file decompilation, analysis, & code exploitation, network man-in-the-middle attacks specific to android devices, and android specific phishing attacks. 

The tools discussed include Kali Linux (various tools, including proxy applications, network sniffers, forensics tools), Android SDK, and ChromeosAPK.

Come to this meeting and learn the strengths (and weaknesses) of Android!

events.name: Google Apps Platform: Using Google’s Calendar API and a Raspberry Pi

events.name: Lego blocks for your browser: Web Components
events.description:
Main Talk:

Web Components (Current Technology Path)

Curious as to what the next evolution in web development may be? 

Looking for a clean way to create a re-usable control for websites other than your own? 

You need to learn about Web Components! 

Web Components are a set of standards currently being produced by Google engineers as a W3C specification that allow for the creation of reusable widgets or components in web documents and web applications.

Andrew Lehman will give you the 411 on Web Components and the following 4 main parts of it:

• Custom Elements 

• Shadow DOM 

• HTML Imports 

• HTML Templates

Andrew is a Programmer at IssueTrak, Inc. with 4 years of experience in web application development. He performed his undergraduate studies in Computer Science at Old Dominion University. He loves studying history and learning to speak/write Mandarin Chinese.

Lightning Talk:

Domain Driven Design (Professional Development Path)

Are you using an object oriented language in your current projects? Is it always a pain to adapt your architecture to meet the changing tech landscape?

DDD (Domain Driven Design) is a great method for keeping your architecture nimble and well organized.

Ken Taylor will give you a short primer on Domain Driven Design and it's benefits.

Ken is a co-organizer for GDG Hampton Roads. He has over 17 years experience in software development. Ken works at IssueTrak, Inc. as the director of development. His hobbies include electronics (arduino, Spark Core, etc.) and experimenting with Google technologies.

events.name: Polymer: Making a better web component by component
events.description:
Main Talk: Polymer 

Web Components usher in a new era of web development based on encapsulated and inter-operable custom elements that extend HTML itself. Built atop these new standards, Polymer makes it easier and faster to create anything from a button to a complete application across desktop, mobile, and beyond.

Danny Cook will show how you can use polymer to make your web applications more extensible and better looking.

Lightening Talk: Functional programming

In computer science, functional programming is a programming paradigm—a style of building the structure and elements of computer programs—that treats computation as the evaluation of mathematical functions and avoids changing-state and mutable data.

Ted Foye will give us the 411 on functional programming and how it is different from the imperative style that most of us are used to and in a lot of cases more efficient!

events.name: Building apps that sign into Google
events.description:
Many apps need to establish the user’s Identity in order to customize the app to the user’s desires, save their data, allow them to identify themselves in social circles and countless other scenarios. There are many ways that you can allow your users to identify themselves, such as implementing a sign in functionality of your own, where you manage your users and their credentials, or, as is becoming increasingly more common, you can allow them to sign in using their credentials from commonly used platforms such as Facebook, Twitter or Google.

In this lab, you’ll learn how to provide sign-in functionality to your Android App, built using Android Studio, using Google Sign-In.

Google Sign-In is a technology that allows you to get users into your apps quickly and securely with little development work required. It allows you to create a seamless experience across screens for your users -- they sign in once, and are authenticated on all of your devices. It allows you to integrate Google’s services into your websites and mobile apps, and also enables over-the-air installation of Android apps when users sign into your web sites. In this lesson you’ll learn how to add Google Sign-In to your android app -- and how to manage the workflow of your users signing into your app.

events.name: Kotlin: From Zero to Hero

Kotlin from Zero to Hero: Learning Kotlin Programming

Come learn the cool new programming language, Kotlin. Google now officially supports Android development using Kotlin. We will be going through the Kotlin Koans exercises with help from professional Kotlin programmer Robert Chrzanowski and Ben Earley.

Prerequisites:

Some experience in an object oriented language (e.g. Java, C#, C++)

Laptop running IntelliJ Community Edition (https://www.jetbrains.com/idea/#chooseYourEdition)

Install Kotlin Educational Plugin (https://blog.jetbrains.com/kotlin/2016/03/kotlin-educational-plugin/)

Bio:

Robert Chrzanowski is a mobile software engineer for Outsite Networks. He has deployed Kotlin in production on Android for over a year. He enjoys learning new programming languages and spending time with his wife Michelle and cats Clover, Moe and Diablo.
